ice_model_used: complicated -- see methods of reference, but an attempt to summarize below: deglaciation -- ICE-6G; From 400 ka to deglaciation, GMSL based on Waelbroeck (at each time assign the icegeometry from the degla ciation that corresponds to the same GMSL value); LIG -- GMSL set to 0; Eurasian ice sheet -- Peltier et al., 2015, Colleoni et al., 2016, Lambeck et al., 2006, Lambeck et al., 2006 with EIS GMSLE of 32, 40, and 47 m. Following the deglacial geometry of GLAC-1D (Tarasov et al., 2014)
ref: Barnett, R.L., Austermann, J., Dyer, B., Telfer, M.W., Barlow, N.L., Boulton, S.J., Carr, A.S. and Creel, R.C., 2023. Constraining the contribution of the Antarctic Ice Sheet to Last Interglacial sea level. Science Advances, 9(27), p.eadf0198.

ice_model_used: two base Earth Structure with 3D perterbations added to them, one following VM5, another with upper mantle of 0.5e21
ref: Austermann, J., Hoggard, M.J., Latychev, K., Richards, F.D. and Mitrovica, J.X., 2021. The effect of lateral variations in Earth structure on Last Interglacial sea level. Geophysical Journal International, 227(3), pp.1938-1960.

ice_model_used: within penultimate glacial maximum and last integlacial; ensemble of potential Eurasian ice sheet histories
ref: Pollard, O.G., Barlow, N.L., Gregoire, L.J. and Gomez, N., 2024. Relative sea-level sensitivity in the Eurasian region to Earth and ice-sheet model uncertainty during the Last Interglacial. Quaternary Science Reviews, 343, p.108908.

ice_model_used: ice models as dyer2021 save with Laurentide disappearance delayed until ~122 ka and Antarctic collapse in the early Last Interglacial
ref: Creel, R.C., Austermann, J., 2024. Glacial isostatic adjustment driven by asymmetric ice sheet melt during the Last Interglacial causes multiple local sea-level peaks. Geology. https://doi.org/10.1130/G52483.1
